	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.47]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Yes....this makes sense. I'd make the assertion that 50 hps has negligible effect on a priest, or necro for that matter, since they typically have a larger hp base than other true casters. A self-healer can replace his hps (lifetap in the case of a necro), while mages, wizards, and enchanters have no capacity to convert mana to hps, and can't afford to lose any of their low-to-begin-with hp base, when they could be wiped out by the mere first notice of a high level mob. A priest (druid maybe a bit less since they have fewer hps and generally lame AC) typically has the ability to survive at least one round of attacks, and can undo the damage to some extent...(necro can try to FD til someone can heal him). Shaman maybe could use a bit less than cleric only because they melee a bit more. Now....since necros and shamen rely on hp to mana conversion, some have made the argument that they shouldnt lose the hps. But do they ever get 125 mana for 50 hps? Don't think so, so they can make just as good use as a cleric of this item. So....best use for this item (just my opinion, dont flame my sorry arse) would be cleric&gt;shaman&gt;necro&gt;druid&gt;wizard&gt;mage&gt;enchanter. By the way.....for those who dont think Zelinthak can be brought down by 6 people, you're wrong. In a group of 7, by no means UBER.....we had him to 25% after 20 minutes, when he gated....If we had known he could do that, we would have brought an enchanter to sieve him, and maybe things would have been different. So if 7 pretty-well equipped good players could do it, I see no reason why 6 disgustingly well-equipped masterful players couldn't OWN this guy. <br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
